# Next.js Core Rules

## Stack and Architecture
- Use Next.js App Router only.
- Use TypeScript in strict mode.
- Use Tailwind CSS for styling.
- Use Prisma ORM with PostgreSQL.
- Organize the codebase with clear separation between UI, server logic, database access, and domain logic.

## Project Structure
- Use `app/` for routes, layouts, route handlers, loading states, and error boundaries.
- Use `components/` for reusable UI components.
- Use `lib/` for utilities, configuration, helpers, validation schemas, and shared server/client helpers.
- Use `server/` or `services/` for business logic and orchestration.
- Use `prisma/` for Prisma schema and migrations.
- Use lowercase directory names with dashes when needed.

## Component Strategy
- Prefer Server Components by default.
- Add `'use client'` only when required for browser interactivity, local UI state, hooks, or client-only APIs.
- Do not convert entire pages to client components if only a small interactive section needs it.
- Keep client components focused and small.

## Data Access
- Never put raw Prisma queries directly inside presentation components unless the file is a small server route/page and the query is trivial.
- Centralize important database access in dedicated server-side modules.
- Keep business rules out of JSX.

## Forms and Validation
- Use Zod for input validation.
- Validate all user inputs on the server even if client validation exists.
- Return structured validation errors.
- Show proper pending, success, and error states in forms.

## State Management
- Minimize client-side global state.
- Prefer server-derived state when possible.
- Use local component state for UI interactions only.
- Use React Context sparingly and only when there is a clear need.

## Performance
- Prefer Server Components and server data fetching where appropriate.
- Use dynamic imports for non-critical heavy client components.
- Optimize images with `next/image` when relevant.
- Avoid unnecessary `useEffect`, `useMemo`, and `useCallback`.
- Do not fetch the same data repeatedly across sibling components when it can be centralized.

## Routing and UX
- Follow App Router conventions.
- Implement `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx`, and `not-found.tsx` where useful.
- Use route handlers for server APIs.
- Keep routes intuitive and business-oriented.

## Styling
- Build a minimal, clean, mobile-first design.
- Prefer utility classes and small reusable UI primitives.
- Avoid flashy animations unless they improve UX.
- The hotel is not luxury-first; the interface should feel trustworthy, simple, and modern.

## Code Quality
- Write small, composable functions.
- Prefer explicit naming over clever abstractions.
- Avoid duplication, but do not over-abstract prematurely.
- Refactor when a file becomes hard to read.
- Do not leave dead code or commented-out obsolete implementations.
- Add comments only when they clarify intent, constraints, or non-obvious decisions.

## Error Handling
- Fail safely and explicitly.
- Never swallow errors silently.
- Log server-side errors in a structured way.
- Return user-friendly messages for expected failures.

## Security
- Never trust client input.
- Protect admin routes and admin APIs.
- Do not expose secrets or internal implementation details to the client.
- Sanitize and validate any rich input.
- Use environment variables for all secrets and connection strings.

## Output Expectations
- Generate production-ready code.
- Prefer maintainability and clarity over cleverness.
- When implementing a feature, include the necessary types, validation, loading states, and error handling.
